<br>
Dune - forget the movie.  Find someone to literally erase it from your mind.  Reading Dune will actually rearrange the way your brain works, it's that good.  The first three were great books, but Dune itself defines masterpiece writing.<br>
<br>
Quasi-sidestepping the genre I'd also recommend reading Stephen King and Peter Straub's The Talisman.  It's not Tolkeinesque wizards and warriors type stuff but it's great fantasy reading.  Kind of a big book but don't let that dissuade you.  It's well worth the investment. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/umenarion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Menarion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(8/12/02 11:14:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19460.topic&index=66>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:(OT)R.A. Salvatore</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I am kinda surprised to see the many referals of the Riftwar Saga and not a single mention of his collaborative work with Janny Wurts that takes place on the Tsurrani (sp?) homeworld.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
